Windows Printing Architecture – Rephrased in Points (Exam-Oriented)
1. Basic Overview
Windows printing architecture consists of two main components:
Print Spooler
Print Drivers
The print spooler is the central and most important part of the printing system.
It is an executable file called spoolsv.exe.
It starts automatically when the system boots and runs until shutdown.
2. Functions of Print Spooler
Decides whether a print job should be processed locally or over a network
Accepts data from GDI (Graphics Device Interface) along with printer drivers
Stores print jobs temporarily in a spool file (spooling process)
Manages the printer queue and selects the next available printer
Converts data from formats like EMF to printer-compatible formats like PCL
Sends processed data to the printer hardware
Maintains printer configuration and settings in the system registry
3. Structure of Printing System
If the printer is local, both client and server components are on the same machine
If the printer is network-based, components are distributed across systems
4. Main Components of Print Spooler System
(a) Application
Creates print jobs using GDI functions
Example: MS Word, browser
(b) GDI (Graphics Device Interface)
Helps applications communicate with printers
Consists of:
User-mode (Win32 GDI) → Used by applications
Kernel-mode (Graphics Engine) → Supports device drivers
(c) Winspool.drv
Acts as the client interface to the spooler
Sends print requests from application to spooler
(d) Spoolsv.exe
Main spooler service (API server)
Manages all printing operations
(e) Spoolss.dll
Works as a router
Determines which print provider to use
Forwards requests to the correct provider
5. Print Providers
Responsible for:
Sending print jobs to local or remote printers
Managing print queues (start, stop, list jobs)
Use standard API functions called by spoolss.dll
Types of Print Providers
localspl.dll → Handles local printers
win32spl.dll → Handles network printers
nwprovau.dll → Used for Novell NetWare printing
inetpp.dll → Handles internet (HTTP/URL) printing
Printer manufacturers can also create custom providers
6. Print Processors
User-mode DLL files
Convert spooled data into a format suitable for printing
Working
Read data from spool file
Convert data into required format
Send converted data back to spooler
Default print processor: winprint.dll
Installed along with printer drivers
7. Print Monitors
Responsible for sending print data from spooler to printer hardware
Types of Print Monitors
(a) Language Monitor
Provides bi-directional communication
Allows printer to send status updates
Adds control information to print data
Can perform post-spooling processing
(b) Port Monitor
Connects spooler with hardware ports
Manages and configures printer ports
Sends data to actual printer device
